{[show NESW]
[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead] Lead the \DA. You overcalled diamonds holding \DA-Q-J-T-8 — cash the ace and keep the lead to look at dummy.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end] West overcalled diamonds and you landed in 4\S — ten tricks, and this time the problem is the TRUMP suit: A-K-7-6 facing J-8-4-3, missing the queen with East likely holding her guarded after the auction placed West with the diamond length. No finesse picks up Q-T-5-2 behind you. So aim the endplay at EAST instead: strip the red suits, then deliberately LOSE the third club to him — and his forced return will solve your trump problem for you.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead] West cashes two diamonds and shifts; win, and strip: hearts around to your K-Q-4 — three rounds, done — then two top trumps (the queen stays guarded, as feared). Clubs now: king, ace... and the THIRD club goes to East's queen on purpose. Count East's choices: his diamonds are gone with a ruff waiting in each hand — a diamond return is a ruff-and-discard; a trump runs from his queen into your king. He returned the trump; your seven — the SEVEN — won a trick, and the ace dropped his queen next. Ten tricks off a suit you could never have picked up alone.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play] The advanced form: the throw-in trick was one you MANUFACTURED — a club you could have finessed, spent instead as the price of the endplay. Two exits, both fatal: the ruff-and-discard or the trump into the tenace. When a guarded queen sits over your ace-king, stop trying to catch her — make her owner throw her under the wheels himself.}
