{[show NESW]
[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead] Lead the \C2, fourth-best from your longest suit — the quiet start against the heart game.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end] Partner transferred, offered 3NT, and your three-card support chose 4\H on the five-three fit. Ten tricks. Now count the trump suit honestly: dummy's A-T-7-4-2 over your Q-8-5 is missing K-J-9-6, and if one defender holds all of that, arithmetic says TWO trump losers — the king, and the jack-nine perched behind dummy's ace-ten. Add a club and a diamond and you are down one. The strip-and-endplay answer: take his king off him at YOUR moment, with every safe exit already burned, and the jack-nine must lead into the ace-ten.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead] East wins the club ace and returns one to dummy's jack. Two top spades — keeping your ace as control — then the diamond ace and your club king. Now a LOW trump from dummy, ducked all around: East's singleton falls, and the count is public — West began with K-J-9-x. Knock out his diamond king, win the return, and play the trump QUEEN: his king takes it, exactly as planned. Look at his three cards: trumps and a club. A club exit is simply ruffed in dummy with his position unchanged, so back come the trumps: the nine rides to dummy's TEN, and the ace collects his jack. Ten tricks — the king scored, the jack-nine never did.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play] Arithmetic said two trump losers; the endplay paid one of them off in a currency the defense could not refuse. The low trump round was the census — East's singleton told you exactly who held the jack-nine — and the queen-to-king play was the throw-in, made only AFTER his side suits were stripped. A defender's trump honor is a fixed asset; a defender's trump SPOTS are only worth what his exit cards let them earn.}
